                  <interp inst="t18240603-237-crimeloc1233" type="placeName" value="Gloucester-place"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18240603-237-crimeloc1233" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18240603-237-off1231 t18240603-237-crimeloc1233"></join>. I was acquainted with the prisoner; he was out of place, and called on me on Saturday, the 29th of May, about three o'clock - I asked him down stairs, and took him into the pantry; he remained there about a quarter of an hour or twenty minutes, and then went away. The plate was in the pantry, and about three hours after he was gone I missed a large fish fork; I had seen it in the morning. I made enquiry, and reported it to my master. I saw it on the Wednesday following.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18240603-237-person2028">
                  ROBERT 
                  MARCHANT
               <interp inst="t18240603-237-person2028" type="surname" value="MARCHANT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240603-237-person2028" type="given" value="ROBERT"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18240603-237-person2028" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I keep a silversmith's shop, in Mortimer-street, Cavendish-square. The prisoner came to me on the Saturday, and asked if I bought old silver - he laid down on the counter a fork, broken in two pieces; I said,</p>
               <p>"I can't buy this, it has got a crest upon it, and is almost a new one;" he said,</p>
               <p>"Give it to me again" - I said,</p>
               <p>"No, I can't, I must send for an officer, and secure you." There were two gentlemen in the shop, and I begged of them to detain him till I got an officer.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
